RATIONALE: When applying biosynthetic engineering approaches at the early stages of drug discovery, e.g. aiming to develop novel tetracycline analogues, target compounds are generally produced by engineered microorganisms in low yields. Rapid and reliable identiﬁcation of metabolites with desired structural modiﬁcation directly from bacterial cultures is therefore of great importance. METHODS: Structural elucidation of atypical tetracyclines was carried out by fragmentation applying electrospray ionisation tandem mass spectrometry (ESI-MS/MS) (triple quadrupole – linear ion trap; Applied Biosystems 4000 QTRAP) and a high-resolution mass spectrometer (Agilent Technologies 6224 TOF). Fragmentation patterns were obtained either with direct injection or by applying separation of target compounds with high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) prior to mass spectrometry. In-source and CID fragmentation were compared. Theoretical calculations of target structures using the Gaussian programme suite were carried out with the aim of strengthening experimental structural elucidation. RESULTS: Recombinant strains of Amycolatopsis sulphurea producing atypical tetracyclines chelocardin, modiﬁed chelocardin analogues (9-demethylchelocardin and 2-carboxyamido-2-deacetyl-chelocardin (CDCHD), and anhydrotetracycline (ATC) were analysed by collision-induced dissociation (CID) fragmentation with higher collision energies to yield structurally important fragments which were identiﬁed. We have demonstrated that ATC is more prone to fragmentation compared to its epimer, which was further supported by comparison of both structures calculated with ab initio calculations. CONCLUSIONS: We have demonstrated that fragmentation patterns of atypical tetracyclines in CID-MS spectra enable rapid structural elucidation of target metabolites produced by cultures of genetically engineered bacteria. This method is of signiﬁcant importance for early stages of drug development considering that isolation of target metabolites produced at low concentration is challenging. Tetracyclines (TC) are members of the polyketide family of natural products, which contain a number of medically important antibacterial drugs such as the ﬁrst-generation TCs oxytetracycline, chlortetracycline and des-methyltetracycline. Natural TCs are obtained from fermentation broths of soil bacteria from the group of Streptomyces spp. and were the ﬁrst major class of therapeutics to earn the distinction "broad-spectrum antibiotic".[1] These natural products of served as a starting point for the discovery of the second and third generations of such as minocycline, doxycycline and relatively recently introduced tigecycline.[2] The ﬁrst two TC members, chlortetracycline and * Correspondence to: M. Unfortunately, extensive use of antibiotics in previously susceptible bacterial populations. For a long time emerging semi-synthetic resistance was neutralised by successful analogues, such as second-generation TCs, doxycycline and minocycline, active against microbes possessing different resistance determinants spreading among pathogenic strains.[4] In recent years a novel group of termed glycylcyclines, has been developed,[5] including tigecycline,[6] which was introduced successfully into clinical practice in 2006.[7] Interestingly, new and promising approaches have been developed recently, where unique TC analogs are produced by synthesis or biosynthetic engineering.[8,9] total caused wide-spread resistance Copyright © 2015 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd. However, these analogues all belong to the so-called ’typical’ TCs conserving their mode of action which is based on binding the ribosome and inhibiting translation.[10] In contrast, chelocardin,[11] and other atypical TCs, seem to display different modes of action,[1,11] a highly desirable property when considering the development of new antibacterials.

The core structure of a typical tetracycline is characterized by four six-membered rings, A, B, C and D, of which the D ring is aromatic (Fig. 1). Chemical modiﬁcation of the upper periphery of the TC backbone has led to compounds with improved characteristics while, chemical modiﬁcation along the ’bottom’ half of the structure, which is essential for binding to the bacterial ribosome and thus inhibiting translation, decreased biological activity.[7,12] On the other hand, several ’atypical’ tetracycline compounds have also been identiﬁed but have so far still not been used in clinical practice, 6- thiatetracycline and ATC, which are characterised by a more planar structure. Remarkably, in their mechanism of action which is believed to involve interference its with the bacterial membrane and disruption of function.[3,13,14] CHD[15] is produced by a rare actinomycete strain Amycolatopsis sulphurea NRRL 2822[16] and displays potent broad-spectrum antibacterial activity.[17] CHD has been shown to be highly active against Gram-positive and some Gram-negative pathogens including Staphylococcus aureus strains and shows potent activity against multi- resistant pathogens.[15,17,18] Although its chemical structure resembles that of typical TCs it has been demonstrated that CHD is likely not a translation inhibitor.[11] Therefore, expected new therapeutic areas, extended structural space of atypical tetracyclines, the continuing pressing need to ﬁght bacterial resistance and rapid development of genome- sequencing based biosynthetic engineering of producing organisms have recently led to a renaissance of tetracycline research with promising new compounds being currently evaluated for a wide variety of therapeutic areas.[19] Analysis of TCs by tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS) is mostly based on multiple reaction monitoring (MRM) transitions, where neutral loss of ammonia, water or in some cases both occurs, understandably, because these are the most abundant transitions.[20–23] For identiﬁcation purposes these transitions are not helpful, because these transitions are the same for all compounds in this class. On the other hand, smaller fragments are in general much more informative for the interpretation of structure. The identiﬁcation of medium size and smaller fragments is necessary for elucidation of novel compounds with similar structure found in fermentation broths. The possibility of rapid determination of whether the target product is present in any in the fermentation broth or not biosynthetic engineering approach towards novel analogues based on known biologically active compounds. It is of signiﬁcant advantage if the structure of a novel product is conﬁrmed before carrying out the isolation steps due to lengthy procedures and large amounts of bacterial culture often needed for isolation. Unfortunately, identiﬁcation of smaller TC fragments has not been tackled yet; the most comprehensive study on TC fragmentation was published by Vartanian et al.,[25] describing the fragments obtained after the neutral loss of ammonia and water, which are common for all TCs in their study. In our recent studies,[17,26,27] a large number of engineered actinomycete strains potentially producing target TC analogues had to be rapidly analysed. The structures of the novel analogues could be predicted based on the targeted genetic modiﬁcations of the producing strains; however, there was a critical need for rapid conﬁrmation of biosynthesised molecules in the fermentation broths. We identiﬁed the most fragments generated with collision-induced abundant dissociation (CID) for CHD and proposed their structures, which were later conﬁrmed with high-resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) measurements. This approach greatly aided our efforts to determine the tentative structures of novel analogues and their corresponding fragments, to be further isolated and later conﬁrmed by nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and HRMS. In this work, CID fragments of CHD and the derivatives and 2-carboxyamido- 9-demethylchelocardin (DMCHD) 2-deacetylchelocardin (CDCHD) are explained. Besides these compounds, two atypical TCs: anhydrotetracycline (ATC) and 4-epianhydrotetracycline (epiATC), were also studied because of their similarity to the novel CHD analogues. The novel compounds (CDCHD and DMCHD) used in the presented study have also been characterised with HRMS, NMR and 2D NMR experiments in our previous studies.[17,26] Analysis of differences in CID spectra of epimers will also enable determination of the stereochemistry of synthesised and isolated TC compounds.

Mass spectrometry was performed using triple quadrupole– linear ion trap (QqQ-LIT) hybrid mass spectrometer (4000 QTRAP LC/MS/MS system; Applied Biosystems/MDS Sciex, Ontario, Canada); resolving power (FWHM) at 121 m/z is 170. For all ﬁve compounds, positive-ion mode was selected: IS (ionisation source voltage + 5500 V); DP (declustering potential + 125 V); EP (entrance potential + 10 V). Direct injection was used for sample introduction with a syringe pump (11plus; Harvard Apparatus, Holliston, MA, USA); a ﬂow rate of –1 was used. Solutions of investigated compounds 10 μL min (Chromasolv LC–MS grade, were prepared in methanol –1. ≥99.9%; Fluka), at a concentration of 20 μg mL High-resolution mass spectra were obtained with a 1260 inﬁnity LC system and a 6224 TOF/LC/MS instrument (both Agilent Technologies). The same solutions were directly injected (0.1 μL per injection) and the fragmentor value was gradually changed from lower to higher voltages to achieve in-source fragmentation. Isocratic elution of the analytes was used and a mobile phase consisting of acetonitrile –1 were (ACN)/water (50:50, v/v) and ﬂow rate of 0.5 mL min employed. Mobile phase was prepared with ACN (Chromasolv for HPLC, ≥99.9%; Sigma–Aldrich) and gradient grade, –1, supplied by a Milli-Q water high-purity water (18.2 MΩcm puriﬁcation system; Millipore, Bedford, MA, USA); resolving (FWHM) power at 121 m/z 9600. The calculations were performed using the Gaussian suite of programs.[28] In all the calculations, the B3LYP/6-31+G(d,p) level of theory was used.

The compounds studied in this work were exposed to collision-induced dissociation (CID), which resulted in many fragments in the mass spectra. The majority of fragments can be interpreted using both MS/MS data and data from the time-of-ﬂight (TOF) mass spectrometer. Because the fragmentation type in the TOF mass spectrometer (in-source fragmentation) differs from the CID fragmentation in the triple quadrupole mass spectrometer, we have compared the data generated by both types of fragmentation and found that both types of fragmentations give identical fragments. The in- source fragmentation in the TOF was achieved by using higher values of fragmentor voltage. At higher fragmentor voltage settings, in-source fragmentation can be initiated in the region between the end of the transfer capillary and the ﬁrst skimmer cone, so that fragmentation increases and the ions detected in MS are not only precursor ions but the fragmentation products as well. In the case of CID fragmentation with low collision energies (CEs) a loss of neutral molecules, i.e. water and ammonia, occurs preferably. However, this fragmentation is not informative enough for structural elucidation; therefore, higher values of CE had to be employed for more pronounced fragmentation. By applying higher excitation voltage the fragmentation patterns were more complex on the one hand, but also more informative on the other, thus enabling us to determine structural information for tetracyclines. Using this approach, in combination with high-resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) of the fragments, we were able to establish the wileyonlinelibrary.com/journal/rcm Copyright © 2015 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd. position of structural differences in the molecule. This is of extreme importance for rapid structural elucidation of new tetracycline analogues biosynthesised by engineered bacterial strains in the fermentation broths. The MS/MS spectra of anhydrotetracycline and 4- epianhydrotetracycline are presented in Fig. 3. The observed fragmentation pattern is in agreement with the data of Vartanian et al.[25] where the base peak in the spectrum with CE set to 40 V is at m/z 410, which corresponds to the neutral loss of ammonia [M+H–NH3]+. Among other intensive peaks, we can resolve the peak at m/z 321 that corresponds to the loss of water, the dimethylamino group and the amido side chain [M+H–H2O–(Me)2N–NH2CO]+. Vartanian et al. proposed two structures for the fragment m/z 154 and our analysis conﬁrms that their structure, assigned as structure A (also depicted in Scheme 2), is the correct one. Beside the three fragments at m/z 154, 321 and 410, we can observe major differences in MS/MS spectra (obtained at the same DP value), between ATC and epiATC for another fragment with m/z value of 269. Relative abundances for fragments of both epimers are presented in Fig. 3. They are as follows: m/z 410 (40%), 321 (25%), 269 (60%) and 154 (100%) for ATC and m/z 410 (100%), 321 (40%), 269 (25%) and 154 (30%) for epiATC, respectively. Differences in peak abundances suggest that there is a signiﬁcant difference in the stability for both epimers. Based on data presented in Scheme 2, we have demonstrated that the fragments with higher m/z, i.e. 410 and 321, are generated with neutral losses of small molecules and the lower two, i.e. 269 and 154, are generated with cleavage of ring A.

these two epimers and to explain the differences in the fragmentation patterns, we carried out ab initio calculations of the structures of these two molecules with the Gaussian program. The calculated structures of both epimers are presented in the Fig. 4. From the calculated structures we can observe that the main difference in molecular conformation is in the orientation of the dimethylamino group in position C4 and consequently the differences in structure are in this part of the molecule. It is evident that rings B, C and D are in the same plane, whereas ring A is bent out of the plane (Fig. 4). In the case of ATC, the dimethylamino group at C4 is oriented away from rings B, C and D, while in epiATC the dimethylamino group is oriented towards the plane. Based on Fig. 4, as can be seen especially well from the ’top’ view of the optimised structures, it is evident that ring A is exposed to collisions from both sides in the case of ATC, whereas, in the case of epiATC, the collision is possible only from one side of ring A because the collision from the other side is ’shielded’ by the dimethylamino group at C4 and would not result in the cleavage of ring A. As a result we can see higher fragments with lower m/z values in the abundance of MS/MS spectrum of ATC, because the interaction of the collision gas and ring A of the analyte molecule is more sterically preferable under CID fragmentation.

The main objective of the present work was to identify the fragmentation patterns of atypical tetracycline structures in CID fragmentation in MS/MS experiments. The structures of the majority of fragments, formed by CID from chelocardin, demethylchelocardin and 2-carboxyamido-2-deacetyl-chelocardin, were proposed and subsequently conﬁrmed with HRMS ex- periments. Our results demonstrate that at higher values of declustering potential (in QqQ) or fragmentor (in TOF), the fragmentation is more pronounced and yields fragments with smaller m/z. These fragments were found to be especially important for structural elucidation of atypical tetracyclines because they are more informative compared to the fragments obtained by neutral loss of smaller molecules (e.g. water, ammonia). The structures of the most abundant fragments of ATC and its epimers have been explained and different fragmentation patterns proposed on the basis of calculated optimised structural conformations which were obtained by ab initio calculations. The obtained results are of great practical importance for rapid structural elucidation of novel compounds of the tetracycline class, synthesized by genetically engineered bacteria. Importantly, biosynthetic engineering approaches often cause reduction in enzymatic activity of the biosynthetic machinery in unexpected ways and therefore can often result in producing unexpected structures, or an array of so-called shunt products Rapid Commun. Thus, rapid and relatively reliable structural determination of the newly occurring compounds in the fermentation broth, produced by engineered strains, is therefore of paramount importance in order to direct future biosynthetic engineering efforts, as well as guide the corresponding isolation procedures.

To summarise, the developed analytical method based on CID-MS/MS fragmentation will signiﬁcantly improve our ability for rapid and reliable structure conﬁrmation directly in the culture of engineered strains, at early stages of drug- development efforts.
